ding references, and gate state. The unit the §6 floors are measured on; \"the injection does not steer tool choice\" is DEFINED as the actual sequence still matching this document. | One exam question for the helper team, written down and locked before the exam — what it's given, what it may touch, and exactly what a right answer looks like. |\n| **Transaction fee** | NYC §20-563.3(c): the card-processing-type fee; capped at 3% of the purchase price per order — no monthly averaging, no refund safe harbor; above 3% only as an exact, documented pass-through of the actual processor charge, with proof available to the department and the establishment on request. | The card-processing fee — a hard 3%, unless they can prove every cent above it is a pure pass-through of real cost. |","tokens":227},"score":0.031746031746031744,"rank":2},{"chunk":{"id":"docs/research/uc1-rule-table.md#1","file":"docs/research/uc1-rule-table.md","anchor":"Answer-first summary · Category","text":"| Category | Cap | Base | Monthly-avg alternative? | Refund safe harbor? |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Delivery fee | **15%** | purchase price / order | Yes (subd. a) | Yes (subd. e) |\n| Basic service fee | **5%** | purchase price / order | Yes (subd. b) | Yes (subd. e) |\n| Transaction fee | **3%** | purchase price / order | **No** | **No** |\n| Enhanced service fee | **20%** | purchase price / order | Yes (subd. d) | Yes (subd. e) |\n| *Anything else* | **forbidden** | — | — | — |\n▸ *Plain: delivery ≤15%, being-listed ≤5%, card-processing ≤3%, optional extras ≤20%, and nothing else allowed. Three of the four can be measured as a monthly average instead of order-by-order, and platforms get a 30-day grace to refund an over-charge on those three — but never on the 3% processing fee.*","tokens":210},"score":0.030834914611005692,"rank":3},{"chunk":{"id":"docs/GLOSSARY.md#19","file":"docs/GLOSSARY.md","anchor":"Glossary · Purchase price base","text":"| **Purchase price base** | \"Purchase price of each online order\" — the statutory base every cap percentage is measured against (§20-563.3(a)–(d)). Its inclusions/exclusions (tax, tip, pre- vs post-discount) are UNVERIFIED as of 2026-07-03 (source-memo U1) — base-derived verdicts are provisional until resolved. | The order amount the percentages apply to — with an honest asterisk: exactly what counts inside it is still an open question. |\n| **Reconciliation** | The operational process of comparing two independent records of the same activity (e.g., POS sales vs platform payout statement) and explaining every difference. | Lining up two versions of the books and accounting for every mismatch, penny by penny. |\n| **Recorded model turn** | A committed, typed decision (`evals/crew/cases/recorded-turns.json`) replayed in place of a live model call during offline trajectory evaluation; an unplanned turn throws loudly rather than defaulting. Steered/hostile recorded turns deliberately simulate a compromised model so what gets measured is the ORCHESTRATOR'S containment. | The \"AI's answer\" comes from a checked-in answer sheet — including some deliberately WRONG answers, to prove the guardrails catch a misbehaving AI. |","tokens":236},"score":0.030309988518943745,"rank":4},{"chunk":{"id":"docs/research/uc1-rule-table.md#4","file":"docs/research/uc1-rule-table.md","anchor":"The rule table · NYC-563.3-d-1","text":"| **NYC-563.3-d-1** | §20-563.3(d) | fee category ∈ {delivery, basic service, transaction, enhanced}; any other fee is unlawful | ▸ only four fee types are legal — anything else is illegal, no matter what it's called | misclassification · relabeling · promotion-deduction mischaracterization · bundling | VERIFIED |\n| **NYC-563.3-d-2** | §20-563.3(d) | enhanced service fee ≤ 20% × purchase price, per order | ▸ optional extras can't exceed 20% | over-cap | VERIFIED |\n| **NYC-563.3-d-3** | §20-563.3(d) | OR monthly average ≤ 20% | ▸ …or 20% averaged over the month | over-cap · relabeling | VERIFIED |\n| **NYC-563.3-d-4** | §20-563.3(d) | charging an enhanced fee ⇒ platform also offers (and charges a basic service fee for) the basic service | ▸ they can only bill \"extras\" if they also offer the plain basic plan | misclassification | VERIFIED |\n| **NYC-563.3-e-1** | §20-563.3(e) | over-cap on a/b/d is not a violation if refunded within 30 days of the month-end; **c excluded** | ▸ a monthly over-charge on delivery/basic/enhanced isn't a violation if refunded within 30 days of month-end — but the 3% processing fee gets no such grace | over-cap · promotion-deduction mischaracterization | VERIFIED |","tokens":260},"score":0.029910714285714284,"rank":5}],"answered":true,"answer_span":"| The \"being listed and findable on the app\" fee — max 5%.","citations":[{"file":"docs/GLOSSARY.md","anchor":"Glossary · Asserted pass-through (unverified)","span":"| **Asserted pass-through (unverified)** | The fee-audit verdict state `asserted-passthrough-unverified` (M2, 2026-07-04): a transaction fee above the 3% cap whose §20-563.3(c)(i)–(ii) pass-through exception rests solely on the platform's own `passthroughDocumented` flag. The statement cannot verify the fee equals the actual processor charge, so the audit surfaces the reliance as a non-gating warn — neither silently cleared nor called a violation. | The platform says an over-3% card fee is \"just passing on the real card cost.\" The bill alone can't prove that either way, so the checker flags it for follow-up instead of trusting it or accusing anyone. |\n| **Audit trail** | An append-only, structured record of every action, decision, and actor in the system, sufficient to reconstruct what happened and why. | A tamper-evident logbook: who did what, when, and on what evidence. |\n| **Basic service fee** | NYC §20-563 (as amended by LL79/2025): the fee for the service that lets a food service establishment receive delivery/pick-up orders on all the platform's sites and be prominently searchable; capped at 5% of the purchase price