## REVISE

1. **P2 — The scoped rule defeats the existing responsive cascade.** [globals.css:2128](/Users/sharan_98/Desktop/curbside-commons/app/globals.css:2128) has specificity `0-2-0`, so it outranks the later breakpoint rules at [globals.css:2194](/Users/sharan_98/Desktop/curbside-commons/app/globals.css:2194) and [globals.css:2210](/Users/sharan_98/Desktop/curbside-commons/app/globals.css:2210). `/fees` therefore remains two-column below 560px instead of folding to one column, potentially recreating ribbon cells on narrow screens. Prefer `:where(.fee-wrap) .rpt-receipts`; it preserves fee scoping while allowing the later breakpoints to win.

2. **P2 — Artifact-mode execution is not evidenced.** The supplied green result names dev e2e only, while the project bar requires dev and artifact. The test is discovered in both configurations, and `setViewportSize` is compatible with both, but run `npm run test:e2e:artifact` against the fixed `out/` before release. My independent runtime attempt was blocked by sandbox port/browser permissions, not by an application failure.

Verified/refuted:

- `/report` and `/demo` are not selected by `.fee-wrap`.
- DOM order is statement, clause, rule, arithmetic; resetting odd children correctly targets cells 1 and 3.
- No other `.fee-wrap` receipt grid is unintentionally affected.
- The `dt` shares the widened grid track and has no clipping rule.
- The print rules are coherent; oversized sections may still fragment when avoidance cannot be satisfied, as defined by the [CSS Fragmentation specification](https://www.w3.org/TR/css-break-3/#breaking-rules).
